The logical end of efforts to make GroupItem a universal gizmo would make GroupItem just an ID and a means to append functionality. That way you will know its name but not what it can do because that depends on what got added and what was taken away.

    A group can only add groups, however, the groups it adds can be rules, attributes, members, methods, data, ...
    So to run a method, a group has find it first - a locate, which may fail
    What is a group then (aside from its ID) ... the sum of its parts and whatever it can find?
    A group may provide no way of knowing what it is intended to be. It can provide access to its contents (which may contain methods) and its data.

What if you could implement this not by adding components in a list but instead redefine the contents of a group on the fly to include addresses of its contents: that is, add a field not an attribute. And how to know what fields it added? Might be able to define a group class to serve as template, such that, if a group is of that class, the class can be accessed to determine its fields (and their location)
    
